We can start by finding the remainders of $4(a_{n-1}+a_{n-2}+a_{n-3})$ when divided by $11$ for $n=3,4,5,\ldots$:
\begin{align*}
4(a_2+a_1+a_0)&\equiv 4(8+5+2)\equiv 1\pmod{11}\\
4(a_3+a_2+a_1)&\equiv 4(a_3+8+5)\equiv 4a_3+1\pmod{11}\\
4(a_4+a_3+a_2)&\equiv 4(a_4+a_3+8)\equiv 4a_4+8\pmod{11}\\
4(a_5+a_4+a_3)&\equiv 4(a_5+a_4+a_3)\equiv 4a_5+7\pmod{11}\\
4(a_6+a_5+a_4)&\equiv 4(a_6+a_5+a_4)\equiv 4a_6+9\pmod{11}\\
&\vdots
\end{align*}
We notice that the remainders repeat every $10$ terms, starting from the fourth term. Specifically, the remainders are $1,4a_3+1,4a_4+8,4a_5+7,4a_6+9,4a_7+6,4a_8+3,4a_9+0,4a_{10}+10,4a_{11}+8$ and so on. Therefore, we have
\begin{align*}
a_{2018}&\equiv 4a_{2017}+7\equiv 4(4a_{2016}+9)+7\equiv 4^2a_{2016}+43\pmod{11}\\
a_{2020}&\equiv 4a_{2019}+6\equiv 4(4a_{2018}+7)+6\equiv 4^3a_{2016}+118\pmod{11}\\
a_{2022}&\equiv 4a_{2021}+3\equiv 4(4a_{2020}+6)+3\equiv 4^4a_{2016}+99\pmod{11}
\end{align*}
Now, we need to find $a_{2016}$. We can continue the pattern above to find that the remainders repeat every $10$ terms starting from the sixth term, and the remainders are $4a_5+7,4a_6+9,4a_7+6,4a_8+3,4a_9+0,4a_{10}+10,4a_{11}+8,4a_{12}+5,4a_{13}+2,4a_{14}+11$ and so on. Therefore, we have
\begin{align*}
a_{2016}&\equiv 4a_{2015}+3\equiv 4(4a_{2014}+10)+3\equiv 4^2a_{2014}+43\pmod{11}\\
a_{2016}&\equiv 4a_{2015}+3\equiv 4(4a_{2014}+10)+3\equiv 4^2a_{2014}+43\pmod{11}\\
&\vdots\\
a_{2022}&\equiv 4^4a_{2016}+99\equiv 4^4(4^2a_{2014}+43)+99\equiv 4^6a_{2014}+100\pmod{11}
\end{align*}
Now, we can substitute these congruences back into the expression we want to evaluate:
\begin{align*}
a_{2018}\cdot a_{2020}\cdot a_{2022}&\equiv (4^2a_{2016}+43)(4^3a_{2016}+118)(4^6a_{2014}+100)\\
&\equiv 2^2a_{2016}(4a_{2016}+11)(2^6a_{2014}+25)\\
&\equiv 2^2\cdot 3\cdot 7\cdot 5\equiv \boxed{420}\pmod{11}
\end{align*}
